    # ── Organic Farming – 100 extended Q&A chunks ─────────────────────────────
    {"text": "Q: What is organic farming? A: Organic farming is a method of crop and livestock production that avoids synthetic fertilisers, pesticides, growth regulators, and livestock feed additives, relying instead on crop rotations, green manures, compost, biological pest control, and mechanical cultivation to maintain soil productivity and control pests.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the key principles of organic farming? A: The four IFOAM principles are Health (sustaining the health of soil, plant, animal, human, and planet), Ecology (basing production on ecological processes), Fairness (equitable relationships for shared environment), and Care (precautionary, responsible management).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic certification obtained in India? A: Farmers apply to an accredited certification body (e.g., APEDA-approved agencies). After a conversion period of at least 3 years, the farm is inspected and certified under the National Programme for Organic Production (NPOP) or Participatory Guarantee System (PGS-India).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the conversion period in organic farming? A: The conversion period is typically 2–3 years during which synthetic inputs are completely withdrawn. Crops grown during this period cannot be sold as certified organic. Soil biology and structure are restored during this phase.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is green manuring and why is it important? A: Green manuring involves ploughing in leafy crops like Dhaincha (Sesbania), Sunhemp, or Cowpea while still green. It adds 60–90 kg N/ha, improves soil organic matter, and enhances microbial activity. Best incorporated 45–50 days after sowing.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: Which biofertilisers are recommended for organic rice cultivation? A: Azolla (fixes 20–30 kg N/ha), BGA (Blue-Green Algae), Azospirillum, and Phosphate-Solubilising Bacteria (PSB) are key biofertilisers for rice. Apply Azolla as mulch or incorporate it 10 days before transplanting.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you prepare compost from farm waste? A: Pile crop residues, animal dung, and kitchen waste in layers (30 cm dry biomass, 5 cm dung/soil). Maintain 50–60% moisture. Turn every 15 days. Compost matures in 60–90 days. Finished compost is dark, crumbly, and earthy-smelling.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is Beejamrut and how is it used? A: Beejamrut is a seed treatment solution made from 20 L water, 5 kg cow dung, 5 L cow urine, 50 g lime, and a handful of farm soil. Seeds are soaked for 6–12 hours before sowing. It suppresses seed-borne fungi and stimulates germination.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of earthworms in organic farming? A: Earthworms decompose organic matter, improve soil aeration and drainage, increase nutrient availability (their casts have 5× more nitrogen, 7× more phosphorus than surrounding soil), and stimulate microbial activity. Vermicompost is produced using Eisenia fetida (red wigglers).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is neem-based pesticide and how is it applied? A: Neem seed kernel extract (NSKE) at 5% concentration repels and disrupts moulting of insects. Prepare by soaking 5 kg neem kernels in 10 L water overnight, filter, and make up to 100 L. Spray every 7–10 days. Effective against aphids, whitefly, and leaf miners.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is crop rotation and how does it benefit organic farms? A: Crop rotation involves growing different crops sequentially on the same land. Benefits: breaks pest and disease cycles, improves soil fertility (legume–cereal rotation adds N), reduces weed pressure, and improves soil structure. Example: Rice → Wheat → Moong (Green Gram).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is intercropping and which combinations are recommended organically? A: Intercropping grows two or more crops simultaneously. Organic combinations: Cotton + Cowpea, Maize + Beans, Sorghum + Pigeonpea, Sugarcane + Onion. Benefits include better land use efficiency, pest disruption, and supplementary income.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is farmyard manure (FYM) prepared and what are its nutrient values? A: FYM is prepared by stacking dung, urine-soaked bedding, and fodder waste for 3–6 months. Well-decomposed FYM contains approximately 0.5% N, 0.25% P₂O₅, and 0.5% K₂O. Apply 10–20 tonnes/ha before sowing.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the benefits of mulching in organic farming? A: Mulching with straw, dry leaves, or plastic film conserves soil moisture (reduces irrigation need by 30–40%), suppresses weeds, moderates soil temperature, prevents erosion, and adds organic matter as it decomposes.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is Trichoderma and how is it used in organic farming? A: Trichoderma viride/harzianum is a beneficial soil fungus that controls soil-borne pathogens like Fusarium, Pythium, and Rhizoctonia. Apply @ 5 kg/ha mixed with compost or FYM. Also used for seed treatment @ 4 g/kg seed.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How can Pseudomonas fluorescens help organic crops? A: Pseudomonas fluorescens produces antibiotics (pyoluteorin, 2,4-DAPG) that suppress soil-borne diseases. It also promotes plant growth by producing phytohormones. Apply 2.5 kg/ha as soil drench or mix with FYM.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the significance of soil organic matter in organic farming? A: Soil organic matter (SOM) feeds soil microbes, improves water holding capacity (1% SOM holds ~170,000 L water/ha), buffers pH, provides slow-release nutrients, and improves soil aggregation. Target SOM >2% for healthy crop production.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is Integrated Pest Management (IPM) in organic context? A: Organic IPM combines cultural (crop rotation, resistant varieties), biological (predators, parasitoids), physical (traps, barriers), and botanical (neem, pyrethrum) methods. Chemical synthetic pesticides are excluded. Threshold-based decisions minimize unnecessary interventions.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you control fungal diseases organically? A: Options include: Bordeaux mixture (copper sulphate + lime) at 1% for downy mildew and blight; Trichoderma soil drench; baking soda spray (1 tsp/L) for powdery mildew; good air circulation through proper spacing; and removal of infected plant debris.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of legumes in organic farming systems? A: Legumes fix atmospheric nitrogen via Rhizobium symbiosis (50–300 kg N/ha/year depending on species). They improve soil structure, provide protein-rich fodder, and reduce dependence on external nitrogen inputs. Include pulses, clovers, or vetches in every rotation.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic inputs are approved under NPOP India? A: NPOP permitted inputs include FYM, vermicompost, compost, green manure, biofertilisers (Rhizobium, Azotobacter, PSB), plant-based pesticides (neem, pyrethrum), Bordeaux mixture, copper-based fungicides, sulphur, and physical traps. Synthetic pesticides and fertilisers are prohibited.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is Bordeaux mixture prepared and used? A: Dissolve 1 kg copper sulphate in 50 L water (solution A). Dissolve 1 kg lime in 50 L water (solution B). Slowly pour A into B while stirring. Test pH >7 with litmus. Apply immediately; do not store. Use for downy mildew, late blight, and bacterial leaf spot.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is Agnihotra farming? A: Agnihotra is a Vedic fire ritual performed at sunrise/sunset using cow dung cakes, ghee, and rice in a copper pyramid. Proponents claim it purifies the atmosphere, enhances soil microbial activity, and improves crop health, though scientific evidence remains limited.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the PGS-India certification system? A: Participatory Guarantee System (PGS-India) is a locally focused quality assurance system where farmers mutually certify each other based on peer review, shared values, and trust. It is government-recognised and suitable for small farmers who cannot afford third-party NPOP certification.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is biodynamic farming? A: Biodynamic farming treats the farm as a self-sustaining organism. It follows a cosmic planting calendar, uses specific preparations (BD 500–508) made from herbs, minerals, and manure in homeopathic doses, avoids external inputs, and maintains biodiversity. Developed by Rudolf Steiner.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you manage weeds organically? A: Methods include: manual weeding, mechanical cultivation (inter-row weeding), mulching (straw, plastic), cover cropping, solarisation (polyethylene sheet for 4–6 weeks suppresses weed seeds), crop competition through optimal spacing, and use of allelopathic crops like Sorghum.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is soil solarisation and when is it used? A: Soil solarisation involves covering moist soil with clear polyethylene film for 4–6 weeks during peak summer. Soil temperatures rise to 50–55°C, killing weed seeds, soil-borne pathogens, and nematodes. Most effective in regions with high solar radiation.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are cover crops and how do they benefit organic systems? A: Cover crops (buckwheat, oats, clover, mustard) are grown during off-season to prevent soil erosion, add organic matter, fix nitrogen (legume covers), suppress weeds, and attract beneficial insects. They are terminated before the next cash crop.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic coconut cultivation managed? A: Apply coir pith compost 50 kg + vermicompost 10 kg/palm/year. Use Trichoderma + Pseudomonas drench for root (wilt) disease. For rhinoceros beetle, install pheromone traps + physical removal. Intercrop with cocoa, banana, or black pepper for additional income.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic measures control root-knot nematodes? A: Apply neem cake @ 250 kg/ha, Paecilomyces lilacinus @ 2.5 kg/ha, or Purpureocillium lilacinum biocontrol agent. Incorporate marigold as trap/barrier crop. Solarise soil during summer. Maintain high organic matter to support nematode-trapping fungi.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the importance of pollinators in organic farming? A: Pollinators (honeybees, stingless bees, butterflies) are essential for fruit and seed set in many crops. Organic farms with diverse flowering plants host higher pollinator populations. Avoid pesticides during flowering; plant hedgerows and wildflower strips to attract beneficial insects.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic sugarcane cultivation practised? A: Apply 25–30 t FYM + 5 t vermicompost/ha as basal dose. Use trash mulching between rows to conserve moisture and suppress weeds. Apply Azospirillum + PSB @ 2 kg/ha. For early shoot borer, release Trichogramma chilonis @ 50,000 eggs/ha.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the Subhash Palekar Natural Farming (SPNF) model? A: SPNF, developed by Padma Shri Subhash Palekar, uses only locally available cow-based inputs (Jeevamrut, Beejamrut, Mulching, Whapasa moisture concept). It requires zero external inputs and zero cost after the first year. Officially promoted by Andhra Pradesh as 'Zero Budget Natural Farming'.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is Whapasa and why is it important? A: Whapasa is the condition of coexistence of air molecules and water molecules in soil, coined by Subhash Palekar. He argues that roots need air as much as water, and traditional flood irrigation destroys this balance. Alternate light sprinkling is recommended.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you organically manage powdery mildew on cucurbits? A: Spray 0.5% potassium bicarbonate, or baking soda (5 g/L) + neem oil (5 ml/L) + liquid soap (2 ml/L). Alternatively apply whey or skimmed milk (10% dilution). Ensure adequate air circulation. Remove infected leaves promptly.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the nutrient contents of commonly used organic manures? A: FYM: 0.5% N, 0.25% P, 0.5% K. Vermicompost: 1.5–2.5% N, 1.5–2% P, 1.5–2% K. Neem cake: 5.2% N, 1% P, 1.4% K. Bone meal: 20–25% P, 3–4% N. Fish meal: 8–10% N, 5–7% P. Use combinations for balanced nutrition.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic cotton cultivation different from conventional? A: Organic cotton avoids GMO seeds, synthetic pesticides, and chemical fertilisers. Uses FYM, vermicompost, neem cake, Trichoderma, and Bt spray (approved). Intercropping with jowar or cowpea repels bollworm. Commands 20–30% price premium in export markets.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is fish amino acid (FAA) and how is it prepared? A: FAA is prepared by fermenting fish waste with jaggery in a 1:1 ratio for 30–60 days in a sealed container. The liquid is filtered and diluted 1:500–1:1000 for foliar spray. It provides amino acids and fish-derived nutrients that stimulate plant growth.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic measures are used for organic wheat production? A: Apply FYM 10 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha as basal. Seed treat with Trichoderma viride 4 g/kg + Azotobacter 5 g/kg. Apply 20 L Jeevamrut/acre at tillering. For Karnal bunt, use hot water seed treatment at 52°C for 10 minutes.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is liquid bio-fertiliser and how is it applied? A: Liquid biofertilisers contain concentrated live microbial cultures. Shelf life 12 months. Applied as seed treatment (10 ml/kg seed), soil drench (5 L/ha), or fertigation. More effective than carrier-based biofertilisers in harsh soil conditions.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of mycorrhizal fungi in organic farming? A: Arbuscular Mycorrhizal Fungi (AMF) colonise roots and extend hyphae into soil, increasing phosphorus and water uptake by 10–100×. They also improve plant resistance to drought and pathogens. Apply AMF @ 5 kg/ha mixed with FYM at sowing. Avoid phosphorus-rich fertilisers that suppress AMF colonisation.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic banana cultivation managed? A: Provide 20 kg FYM + 5 kg vermicompost + 500 g neem cake per plant per year. Use Azospirillum + PSB + Trichoderma as biofertiliser package. For Fusarium wilt, use resistant varieties (e.g., Nendran, Robusta) and soil drench with Pseudomonas fluorescens 2 kg/ha.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the importance of biodiversity in organic farming? A: High biodiversity (crop diversity, hedgerows, wildflower strips) supports natural enemies of pests, pollinators, soil organisms, and nutrient cycling. It reduces risk from a single crop failure, improves ecosystem resilience, and maintains genetic resources.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is biochar and how does it benefit organic soils? A: Biochar is charcoal produced by pyrolysis of biomass at 350–700°C with limited oxygen. It is highly stable, resists decomposition for centuries, improves water and nutrient retention, increases soil pH, and provides habitat for beneficial microbes. Apply @ 2–5 t/ha mixed with compost.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you control aphids organically? A: Spray neem seed kernel extract (NSKE) 5%, tobacco decoction (25 g tobacco + 5 g soap/L), or garlic extract (50 g garlic + 5 ml soap/L). Introduce Chrysoperla carnea (green lacewing) or Coccinella septempunctata (ladybird beetle) as biological control. Yellow sticky traps also reduce aphid populations.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the recommended organic protocol for tomato cultivation? A: Apply FYM 20 t/ha + vermicompost 5 t/ha. Seed treat with Trichoderma. Use raised beds and drip irrigation. For early blight, spray copper oxychloride 0.3%. For whitefly, use yellow sticky traps + neem oil. Intercrop with basil or marigold as repellent border.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the advantages of organic farming over conventional farming? A: Advantages: healthier soil and water, reduced chemical residues in food, lower input costs after transition, premium market prices, improved farm biodiversity, carbon sequestration, and better resilience to climate extremes. Disadvantages: lower initial yields, higher labour requirements, and need for certification.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of Azotobacter in organic farming? A: Azotobacter chroococcum is a free-living, aerobic nitrogen-fixing bacteria that fixes 20–30 kg N/ha/year. It also produces growth hormones (IAA, GA) and vitamins. Apply @ 5 kg/ha as soil treatment mixed with FYM or as seed treatment @ 5 g/kg seed.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is Rhizobium biofertiliser used and which crops benefit? A: Rhizobium forms symbiotic nodules on legume roots, fixing 50–300 kg N/ha/year depending on the crop. Specific strains are needed for each legume. Treat seeds with Rhizobium culture @ 200 g/10 kg seed just before sowing. Cowpea, soybean, chickpea, groundnut, and lentils benefit most.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is on-farm seed production in organic systems? A: Growing seeds on the farm ensures genetic purity, local adaptation, and eliminates the need to buy seeds every season. Select healthy, vigorous plants with desired traits. Isolate flowering crops to prevent cross-pollination. Dry seeds to <10% moisture and store in airtight containers with neem leaves.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming contribute to climate change mitigation? A: Organic farms sequester more carbon in soil through higher organic matter inputs. Eliminating synthetic fertilisers reduces N₂O emissions. Diverse agro-ecosystems are more resilient to extreme weather. Studies show organic soils can sequester 50–150 kg C/ha/year more than conventional.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of late blight in potato? A: Apply Bordeaux mixture 1% at the onset of symptoms. Preventive copper oxychloride 0.3% spray every 7–10 days during humid conditions. Use resistant varieties (Kufri Jyoti). Avoid overhead irrigation. Destroy infected plant debris. Observe at least 3-year rotation with non-solanaceous crops.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the importance of water conservation in organic farming? A: Organic soils with higher organic matter hold more water and reduce irrigation frequency. Practices like mulching, contour bunding, rainwater harvesting ponds, and drip irrigation collectively reduce water use by 40–60% compared to flood-irrigated conventional systems.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you organically manage the fruit borer in brinjal? A: Use pheromone traps (Leucinodes orbonalis lure) @ 5/ha for monitoring. Clip and destroy borer-infested shoots weekly. Apply Bt (Bacillus thuringiensis) @ 2 g/L for young larvae. Spray neem oil 3% every 7 days. Use reflective mulch to deter adult moths.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic inputs help improve soil physical properties? A: Vermicompost, FYM, crop residue mulch, green manure, biochar, and coir pith compost all improve soil aggregation, reduce bulk density, increase water infiltration, and enhance aeration. Regular organic matter addition is the single most important practice for long-term soil health.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is fermented plant juice (FPJ) and how is it made? A: FPJ (Korean Natural Farming) is made by packing fresh plant materials (growing tips, aromatic herbs) with brown sugar in a 1:1 ratio. Ferment 7 days in a dark, cool place. Filter and store. Dilute 1:500 for foliar spray to improve plant vigour and stress tolerance.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming affect food nutritional quality? A: Studies show organic produce tends to have higher antioxidants (20–40%), polyphenols, and vitamin C compared to conventional, due to mild biotic stress activating plant defence compounds. However, differences in macronutrient content (protein, carbohydrate) are generally minimal.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of diamondback moth (DBM) in cabbage? A: Apply Bt var. kurstaki @ 2 g/L when larvae are in early instars. Use pheromone traps @ 10/ha. Spray neem oil 3% + soap solution. Introduce Cotesia plutellae as parasitoid. Practise crop rotation; avoid consecutive brassica crops.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic paddy (rice) cultivation managed? A: Apply FYM 5 t/ha + Azolla as green manure. Seed treat with Trichoderma + Pseudomonas. Maintain AWD (Alternate Wetting and Drying) for water saving. For BPH, drain field for 5–7 days. For blast, use resistant varieties and spray fermented garlic-chilli extract.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are organic solutions for controlling termites in fields? A: Drench soil with neem oil emulsion 0.3%. Apply neem cake @ 250 kg/ha at sowing. Use wood ash or diatomaceous earth around plant base. Biological control: Steinernema (entomopathogenic nematode) or Metarhizium anisopliae fungus at 5×10⁹ conidia/ha.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of collar rot in groundnut? A: Seed treat with Trichoderma viride 4 g/kg + Carbendazim (if not strictly organic) or Pseudomonas fluorescens 10 g/kg. Apply FYM enriched with Trichoderma as basal. Avoid waterlogging. Practice 3-year rotation with non-legumes.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the concept of allelopathy and its use in organic farming? A: Allelopathy is the inhibition of one plant by another through chemical release (allelochemicals). Sorghum leachate suppresses weed germination. Sunflower, eucalyptus, and rye release allelochemicals. Used as cover crop mulch or living mulch to reduce weed pressure without herbicides.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic protocol for mango orchard management? A: Apply FYM 50 kg + vermicompost 10 kg + neem cake 5 kg per tree annually. For mango hopper, spray neem oil 0.5% at panicle emergence. For fruit fly, use methyl eugenol traps. For powdery mildew, apply wettable sulphur 0.2% at bud-burst stage.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is wood vinegar (pyroligneous acid) used in organic farming? A: Wood vinegar, a by-product of charcoal making, contains acetic acid, phenols, and alcohols. Diluted 1:200 for foliar spray, it promotes root growth, repels insects, and suppresses some plant diseases. It is considered a natural plant growth stimulant.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the importance of buffer zones in organic farms? A: Buffer zones (hedgerows, uncultivated strips, tree rows) separate organic from conventional fields, prevent pesticide drift contamination, provide habitat for beneficial insects and birds, reduce erosion, and moderate microclimate. NPOP requires a minimum buffer of 7.5 m from conventional farms.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic inputs are effective for potassium nutrition? A: Wood ash (5–7% K₂O, water-soluble), granite dust (3–5% K, slow release), compost (0.5–1% K), and banana stem/peel ash are key organic potassium sources. Vermicompost and FYM also supply K. Feldspar powder releases K over months through weathering.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming practised in hill and tribal areas? A: Hill farmers traditionally use jhum (shifting cultivation), mixed cropping, and forest-based inputs. Modern organic practices add vermicomposting, biofertilisers, and SRI (System of Rice Intensification). Tribal areas like Sikkim have achieved 100% organic status using community-based approaches.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the System of Rice Intensification (SRI) and is it compatible with organic farming? A: SRI uses young seedlings (8–12 days), single transplanting, wider spacing (25×25 cm), intermittent irrigation, and mechanical weeding. It reduces seed use by 80–90%, water by 25–50%, and increases yields 20–100%. Fully compatible with organic inputs.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you test whether compost is mature before application? A: Signs of mature compost: dark brown colour, earthy smell, temperature equal to ambient, no recognisable original materials, pH 6.5–7.5, C:N ratio <20:1. A quick test: place compost in a sealed bag; no foul smell after 3 days indicates maturity.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are pheromone traps and how are they used organically? A: Pheromone traps lure male insects using species-specific sex pheromones. Used for monitoring and mass trapping of Helicoverpa, spodoptera, and fruit fly. Install @ 5/ha at crop height. Replace lure every 3–4 weeks. Reduces need for pesticide sprays when pest population is below threshold.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to soil reclamation of sodic (alkaline) soils? A: Apply gypsum (calcium sulphate) @ 2–4 t/ha to displace sodium. Incorporate Dhaincha green manure, apply large quantities of FYM (20+ t/ha), and leach salts with good irrigation. Grow salt-tolerant crops (Sesbania, Karnal grass) initially. Takes 3–5 years for full reclamation.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming support rural livelihoods? A: Organic farming reduces external input costs, commands premium prices (20–50% over conventional), creates employment in processing and certification, revives traditional knowledge, and encourages farmer cooperatives that improve bargaining power. Women's SHGs are often central to organic production clusters.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of birds in organic pest management? A: Birds like mynah, kingfisher, and owls consume large quantities of insects, rodents, and grasshoppers. Install bird perches (T-shaped bamboo poles @ 25/ha) in fields. Avoid rodenticides and insecticides that kill birds secondarily. Grow berry-producing trees on farm periphery.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is tobacco decoction spray and how is it prepared? A: Boil 250 g tobacco leaves in 4 L water for 30 minutes. Cool, filter, add 30 g soap, and dilute to 10 L. Spray on leaf undersides against sucking pests (aphids, thrips, mites). Use with caution; nicotine is toxic to bees. Avoid near bee hives.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming affect groundwater quality? A: By eliminating synthetic nitrates, organic farming significantly reduces nitrate leaching into groundwater. Studies show organic farms have 30–50% lower nitrogen leaching. Reduced pesticide runoff also improves water body quality for aquatic life.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of black rot in cabbage? A: Use hot water seed treatment at 50°C for 30 minutes. Apply copper-based bactericide (copper hydroxide). Remove infected plants immediately. Rotate with non-cruciferous crops for 2–3 years. Ensure proper field drainage to reduce disease incidence.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is agro-forestry and how does it support organic farming? A: Agro-forestry integrates trees with crops or livestock. Benefits: biomass for compost, shade for understorey crops, nitrogen fixation (Leucaena, Gliricidia), habitat for beneficial insects, income diversification, and carbon storage. Suitable systems: taungya, home gardens, alley cropping.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing Fusarium wilt in vegetables? A: Apply Trichoderma viride 5 kg/ha + FYM as basal. Soil solarise before planting. Use resistant/tolerant varieties. Avoid waterlogging. Apply soil drench with Pseudomonas fluorescens at transplanting. Remove and destroy wilted plants promptly. Rotate with cereals or alliums.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic inputs supply phosphorus to crops? A: Rock phosphate (18–20% P₂O₅, slow-release), bone meal (20–25% P₂O₅), vermicompost, FYM, and phosphate-solubilising bacteria (PSB) convert fixed P to available form. Mycorrhizal inoculation further enhances phosphorus uptake without additional P inputs.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic control of spider mites in vegetable crops? A: Spray neem oil (2%) + soap solution (0.5%). Sprinkle diatomaceous earth on leaves. Apply garlic extract (50 g/L). Introduce predatory mite Phytoseiulus persimilis at 5–10 mites/plant. Maintain adequate humidity; spider mites prefer hot, dry conditions.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the challenges of organic farming in India? A: Key challenges: lower yields during initial conversion (20–30% reduction), lack of certified organic inputs, poor supply chain for premium markets, high certification costs for small farmers, limited awareness among extension workers, risk of contamination from neighbouring conventional farms.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the Sikkim Organic Mission and what were its outcomes? A: Sikkim became India's first fully organic state in 2016 after converting 75,000 ha to organic. Key outcomes: 25–30% increase in tourist arrivals, premium prices for spices and vegetables, improved soil health, and increased farmer incomes. It received the UN Future Policy Award in 2018.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you prevent cross-contamination in organic farms? A: Maintain buffer zones (minimum 7.5 m from conventional), use physical barriers (hedgerows, ditches), implement separate equipment and storage, maintain detailed record-keeping, and conduct regular inspection of field boundaries and water sources.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of brown plant hopper (BPH) in rice? A: Drain the field intermittently (AWD technique) to break the BPH life cycle. Spray 0.03% neem oil or fish oil resin soap. Avoid excess nitrogen. Maintain plant spacing as per SRI (25×25 cm). Release spider (Lycosa pseudoannulata) as predator.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic method to improve nitrogen availability in degraded soils? A: Grow nitrogen-fixing green manure crops (Dhaincha, Sunhemp, Horsegram). Inoculate with Azotobacter and Rhizobium. Apply vermicompost 5 t/ha. Use fish meal or blood meal (6–12% N) for quick release. Mulch with legume residues to conserve mineralised N.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the ZBNF (Zero Budget Natural Farming) movement in India? A: ZBNF was popularised by Subhash Palekar and adopted at state level in Andhra Pradesh (now Rythu Sadhikara Samstha). It aims for zero input cost using cow-dung-based preparations. By 2023, over 700,000 farmers were practising ZBNF in Andhra Pradesh alone.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How are organic farms record-keeping requirements met for certification? A: Organic farms must maintain: farm maps, input purchase records, field operation logs (sowing, irrigation, pest control), yield records, and sales documentation. Records must be kept for at least 5 years and be available for annual third-party inspection.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of soft rot in ginger? A: Treat seed rhizomes with Trichoderma viride suspension + Pseudomonas fluorescens for 30 minutes before planting. Apply FYM enriched with biocontrol agents as basal. Ensure good drainage. Remove and destroy infected clumps. Avoid replanting ginger in the same field for 3–4 years.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic turmeric cultivation managed? A: Apply FYM 25–30 t/ha + vermicompost 3–4 t/ha. Treat rhizomes with Trichoderma. For leaf blotch, spray Bordeaux mixture 1%. For rhizome rot, drench with Pseudomonas fluorescens. Mulch with dry leaves @ 15 t/ha. Harvest 8–9 months after planting.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What role does animal integration play in organic farming systems? A: Integrating livestock provides manure (fertiliser), draught power, weed control by grazing, and diversified income. Animals can graze crop residues reducing waste. Manure from animals fed on organic produce is higher quality. This closed nutrient cycle is a cornerstone of organic farm design.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing viral diseases in crops? A: Manage insect vectors (aphids, whitefly, leafhoppers) through neem oil spray, sticky traps, and reflective mulches. Remove and destroy infected plants. Use resistant varieties. Maintain weed-free borders to limit virus reservoirs. No curative treatments exist — prevention is the only strategy.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming affect bee populations and honey production? A: Organic farms support higher bee diversity and populations due to diverse flowering plants, absence of neonicotinoids, and suitable nesting habitats. Integrating beehives (4–8 hives/ha) improves pollination by 20–30%, increasing fruit set and seed quality while producing marketable honey.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the economic analysis of switching to organic farming? A: During conversion (years 1–3), yields drop 15–30% while costs may remain similar, reducing profit. Post-conversion, input cost savings (30–50%) and price premiums (20–50%) typically restore and often exceed previous profit levels. Long-term soil health improvements also reduce remediation costs.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to maize cultivation? A: Apply FYM 10 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha + neem cake 250 kg/ha as basal. Seed treat with Azospirillum + PSB. For FAW (Fall Armyworm), apply Bt at egg hatching stage + Spinetoram spray. Intercrop with cowpea for nitrogen and FAW disruption.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How are beneficial insects conserved on organic farms? A: Plant insectary strips with umbellifers (dill, coriander, fennel) that attract predatory wasps and hoverflies. Avoid broad-spectrum sprays. Maintain leaf litter and hollow stems for overwintering. Use selective botanical pesticides only when pest threshold is exceeded. Create refuge areas for natural enemies.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the significance of soil pH in organic nutrient availability? A: pH 6.0–7.0 maximises availability of most nutrients. Below 5.5: molybdenum and calcium become deficient, aluminium and manganese toxicity increases. Above 7.5: iron, zinc, manganese, and boron become unavailable. Organic matter helps buffer pH changes; lime or gypsum are pH-correcting inputs allowed under NPOP.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is organic aquaculture and how is it practised? A: Organic aquaculture avoids synthetic feeds, antibiotics, and growth hormones. Fish are raised at low stocking densities. Feed consists of natural plankton, organic fishmeal, or duckweed. Waste water is recycled to irrigate crops (integrated rice-fish farming). Certification under NPOP covers freshwater fish.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic chilli cultivation managed? A: Apply FYM 15 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha. Seed treat with Trichoderma. For thrips, spray spinosad (allowed in some organic standards) or neem oil 3%. For Chilli Mosaic Virus, manage aphid vectors with neem. Use drip irrigation with mulch to reduce soil-borne diseases.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of worm castings (vermicast) in plant nutrition? A: Vermicast is 5× richer in available N, 7× in P, 3× in exchangeable K, and 1.5× in Ca compared to surrounding soil. It contains beneficial microbes, plant hormones (IAA), humic acids, and enzymes that boost root growth, nutrient absorption, and disease resistance.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the key global standards for organic farming certification? A: Major standards: USDA NOP (USA), EU Organic Regulation (EU 2018/848), IFOAM Norms (international), India NPOP, JAS (Japan), Bio Suisse (Switzerland). Standards differ in allowed inputs, conversion periods, and livestock requirements. Export markets require country-specific certification.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does organic farming support food sovereignty? A: Organic farming uses locally available inputs, saves traditional seed varieties, reduces dependence on multinational input companies, and builds community seed banks. It preserves indigenous knowledge systems and empowers farmers to be self-reliant rather than tied to commercial supply chains.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of early blight in tomato? A: Apply Bordeaux mixture 1% or copper oxychloride 0.3% at first symptom. Remove and destroy infected lower leaves. Maintain adequate potassium nutrition (improves disease resistance). Practice crop rotation (2–3 years). Mulch to prevent soil-splash infection.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic measures prevent post-harvest losses? A: Proper drying (below 14% moisture for grains), clean and dry storage, neem leaf layering in grain stores, diatomaceous earth dusting (0.5 kg/100 kg grain), hermetic storage bags (Purdue Improved Crop Storage), and cold storage for perishables. Avoid mixing old and new stocks.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is humus and why is it important in organic farming? A: Humus is the stable, dark-coloured end product of organic matter decomposition. It has a high cation exchange capacity (200–400 cmol/kg), holds water, provides slow-release nutrients, chelates micronutrients, promotes soil aggregation, and feeds soil microorganisms. Building humus is a primary long-term goal of organic farming.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},

    # ── Organic Input Preparation – 50 How-to Q&A chunks ──────────────────────
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Jeevamrut at home? A: In a 200 L drum add 10 kg fresh cow dung, 10 L cow urine, 2 kg jaggery, 2 kg chickpea (besan) flour, and a handful of undisturbed soil from your farm bund. Fill with water to 200 L. Stir clockwise for 5 minutes to aerate. Cover with jute and ferment in shade for 48 hours, stirring once daily. Apply 200 L/acre via drip or flood irrigation or spray undiluted on soil.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Beejamrut for seed treatment? A: Mix 5 kg fresh cow dung, 5 L cow urine, 50 g slaked lime (calcium hydroxide), and a handful of fertile farm soil in 20 L water. Stir well and let it settle for 12 hours. Filter through cloth. Soak seeds in this solution for 20–30 minutes (rice/wheat) or coat rhizomes for 6 hours (ginger/turmeric). Shade-dry for 30 minutes before sowing.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Panchagavya? A: Combine 5 products of the cow: 1 kg cow dung + 1 L cow urine + 1 L cow milk + 250 mL curd + 250 mL ghee. Mix thoroughly and ferment in a clay pot for 7 days, stirring thrice daily. After fermentation add 3 L tender coconut water, 3 ripe bananas (mashed), and 500 mL sugarcane juice. Ferment another 15 days. Dilute to 3% (30 mL/L) for foliar spray.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare vermicompost at home? A: Build a shaded bin (1 m × 2 m × 0.3 m) with drainage holes. Add a 5 cm bedding layer of coconut coir. Introduce 1 kg Eisenia fetida (red wigglers) per 10 kg organic waste. Feed kitchen/farm waste in thin layers every 3–4 days. Maintain 70% moisture (squeeze test: a few drops). Harvest black, granular vermicompost in 45–60 days from the bottom layer.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare neem seed kernel extract (NSKE) 5%? A: Sun-dry neem seeds for 3–4 days. Remove shells and grind kernels to powder. Soak 5 kg neem kernel powder in 10 L water overnight (12 hours). Filter through double cloth to remove solids. Add 30 g soap (as emulsifier) and make up volume to 100 L with water. Spray immediately; NSKE loses potency within 8 hours of preparation.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Dashparni Ark (ten-leaf extract)? A: Collect 2 kg leaves each of: neem, custard apple, papaya, pomegranate, castor, guava, drumstick, lantana, carrot grass (Parthenium), and bael (total 10 types). Add 2 kg green chilli, 2 kg garlic, 500 g ginger, 2 L cow urine, and 2 kg cow dung. Add 200 L water and ferment for 30 days stirring daily. Filter and dilute 3–5% for spraying against sucking pests and mites.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Agniastra (fire arrow botanical spray)? A: Boil 10 L cow urine on low flame. Add 500 g tobacco leaf powder, 500 g green chilli paste, 250 g garlic paste, and a handful of neem leaves. Boil for 15 minutes and cool overnight. Filter and dilute 3% (300 mL/10 L) for spraying. Effective against caterpillars, borers, and hard-bodied insects. Spray at dusk; keep away from eyes.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Brahmastra botanical insecticide? A: Boil 3 L cow urine. Add 3 kg neem leaves, 2 kg custard apple leaves, 2 kg papaya leaves, 2 kg guava leaves, and 2 kg pomegranate leaves. Boil for 20 minutes. Cool, filter, and store in a glass container for up to 6 months. Dilute 3% for field spray. Effective against all types of caterpillars and borers.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare fermented plant juice (FPJ)? A: Collect 1 kg of fast-growing plant tips (sweet potato, banana, morning glory, or aromatic herbs) in the early morning before sunrise. Chop coarsely and mix with 1 kg brown sugar (1:1 ratio) in a ceramic or glass jar. Pack tightly, cover with paper (not airtight), and ferment for 7 days at room temperature. Filter, bottle, and store for up to 1 year. Dilute 1:500 for foliar spray.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare fish amino acid (FAA) organic fertiliser? A: Mix 1 kg fresh fish waste (offal, small bait fish) with 1 kg brown sugar (1:1 ratio) in a container. Stir to coat all fish pieces. Seal with paper or cloth (not airtight). Place a weight on top to keep material submerged. Ferment for 30–60 days at room temperature. Strain liquid; dilute 1:500–1:1000 for foliar spray or soil drench.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Oriental Herbal Nutrient (OHN)? A: Finely chop 100 g each of garlic, ginger, turmeric, cinnamon, and angelica root (or substitute licorice/ashwagandha). Layer with brown sugar (1:1). Add 30% volume of rice wine or local alcohol. Ferment in a sealed jar for 7–30 days. Strain and store. Dilute 1:1000 as a soil drench or seed soak. OHN activates soil microorganisms and provides plant immune stimulation.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare water-soluble calcium (WCA) from eggshells? A: Roast clean eggshells in an iron pan until slightly browned. Cool and place shells in a jar. Pour raw rice vinegar (or apple cider vinegar) at 10:1 ratio (vinegar:shells). Bubbling occurs as calcium dissolves. Loosely cover and leave for 7–10 days. Filter. Dilute 1:1000 as foliar spray during fruiting to prevent blossom-end rot and improve cell wall strength.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare lactic acid bacteria (LAB) serum? A: Fill a jar 2/3 with washed rice-wash water (milky water from rinsing rice). Cover with paper and leave at room temperature for 5–7 days. White froth forms; skim off and keep the clear liquid below. Add 10 parts fresh milk to 1 part rice-water culture. After 5–7 days, curds separate from yellowish LAB serum. Collect the serum; dilute 1:1000 for soil drench to suppress harmful pathogens.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare wood vinegar (pyroligneous acid) from biomass? A: During slow wood/bamboo charcoal burning in a kiln, collect the dark smoke condensate from a side pipe kept at 80–100°C. Let the collected liquid settle for 3 months: tar sinks, light oil floats, and the middle reddish-brown fraction is usable wood vinegar. Dilute 1:200 for foliar spray to stimulate roots, repel insects, and improve fruit colour.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare garlic extract pesticide? A: Peel and blend 100 g garlic cloves with 500 mL water. Strain through fine cloth. Add 5 mL liquid soap as emulsifier and dilute to 10 L. Spray directly on plants to repel aphids, whitefly, spider mites, and fungal gnats. Prepare fresh before each use; loses efficacy after 24 hours. Avoid spraying in direct sunlight; apply in early morning or evening.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare chilli-garlic spray for pest control? A: Blend 100 g fresh green chillies + 100 g garlic + 1 L water. Strain. Add 5 mL soap and dilute to 10 L. Spray on leaf undersides every 5–7 days. Repels and irritates sucking insects (aphids, thrips, mites). Wear gloves and avoid touching eyes during preparation. Do not spray during pollination as it repels bees.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare tobacco decoction spray? A: Boil 250 g dried tobacco leaves or cigarette butts in 4 L water for 30 minutes. Cool, strain, and add 30 g soap dissolved in warm water. Make up to 10 L with water. Spray on affected plants, targeting leaf undersides. Effective against aphids, thrips, leaf miners, and caterpillars. Toxic to bees; never spray near beehives or on open flowers.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare cow urine (gomutra) spray? A: Collect fresh cow urine from a desi (indigenous) cow in a mud pot or glass jar. Dilute fresh urine 1:10 with water for foliar spray on crops as a growth stimulant. For pest management dilute 1:5 and add 0.5% neem oil. Fermented gomutra (aged 15 days) is more potent and acts as both fertiliser and fungicide. Apply once a week in the evening.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare neem oil emulsion for spraying? A: Mix 10 mL cold-pressed neem oil with 2 mL liquid soap (as emulsifier) in a small cup. Slowly add this pre-mix to 1 L warm water while stirring constantly. Never add oil directly to water. Spray immediately, as emulsion separates within 8 hours. Use 3% (30 mL neem oil/L) for pest control and 1% (10 mL/L) as a weekly preventive spray.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare coir pith compost? A: Wet 100 kg coir pith (dried coconut husk fibre) to 70% moisture. Spread in 30 cm layers alternating with 5 kg Pleurotus fungal culture (or Trichoderma). Top with 5 kg urea or 20 kg FYM to provide nitrogen (coir pith has a very high C:N ratio of 100:1). Turn monthly. After 90–120 days coir pith decomposes to a dark, spongy compost with C:N ratio <20:1.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare enriched organic compost with biofertilisers? A: Once compost reaches near-maturity (45 days), inoculate with 2 kg Trichoderma viride + 2 kg Pseudomonas fluorescens + 2 kg Azotobacter per tonne of compost. Mix thoroughly and keep moist for another 7–10 days. This 'fortified compost' delivers both nutrients and beneficial microbes to the soil in a single application.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare biochar and apply it to soil? A: Fill a metal drum with dry biomass (crop stalks, wood chips, rice husk). Ignite from the top; restrict airflow so biomass smoulders rather than burns. When smoke turns white-blue, quench with water. Crush to <2 mm pieces. Charge the biochar by soaking in Jeevamrut or compost tea for 48 hours before application. Apply charged biochar at 2–5 t/ha mixed with FYM.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Sasyagavya liquid organic fertiliser? A: Ferment 10 kg fresh cow dung + 10 L cow urine + 5 kg neem leaves + 2 kg calotropis leaves + 2 kg Vitex leaves in 100 L water for 10 days. Stir daily. Filter and dilute 5% (5 L in 100 L water) for soil drench or 3% for foliar spray. Provides broad-spectrum nutrients and acts as a mild insect repellent.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare green manure from Dhaincha (Sesbania)? A: Sow Dhaincha @ 20–25 kg seed/ha in the main field before the monsoon crop. When it is 45–50 days old (before flowering), cut and turn it into the soil using a cultivator. Allow 10–15 days for decomposition before planting the next crop. Dhaincha adds 60–90 kg N/ha, 15–20 t green biomass/ha, and improves soil structure significantly.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Trichoderma enriched FYM? A: Spread 1 tonne of semi-decomposed FYM in a shaded area. Dissolve 1 kg Trichoderma viride talc formulation in 5 L water and sprinkle uniformly over the FYM. Mix well, cover with moist jute, and leave for 7–10 days at 25–30°C. The white mycelium visible on the surface indicates successful colonisation. Apply directly to soil at transplanting.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare bone meal for organic farming? A: Collect animal bones from slaughterhouses. Boil for 1–2 hours to remove fat. Dry completely in sun for 3–5 days. Crush and grind to a coarse powder. Raw bone meal contains 22–24% P₂O₅ and 3–4% N. Steam bone meal (autoclaved) has faster availability. Apply @ 100–200 kg/ha as basal dose by mixing in soil during land preparation.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare potassium-rich wood ash for crops? A: Collect ash from burning crop residues, wood, or coconut shells. Avoid ash from treated wood or plastics. Store dry; moisture causes potassium to leach. Apply 500 kg/ha broadcast before the last ploughing. Alternatively dissolve 1 kg ash in 10 L water, settle overnight, and use the clear solution as foliar spray (1:5 dilution) to supplement potassium and raise soil pH.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Amrit Pani (nectar water) for crops? A: Mix 10 kg fresh cow dung + 1 L cow urine + 250 g jaggery in 200 L water. Stir well and apply immediately (no fermentation needed) as a soil drench @ 200 L/acre at sowing and after transplanting. Amrit Pani activates native soil microbes, provides instant sugars for microbial growth, and stimulates seedling root development.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare compost tea for foliar feeding? A: Fill a cloth bag with 500 g mature compost. Suspend it in 10 L water in a bucket. Aerate with an aquarium pump for 24–48 hours (aerobic compost tea). Remove the bag. Apply the tea undiluted as foliar spray within 4 hours, as microbial populations decline rapidly. Compost tea delivers beneficial bacteria and fungi directly onto plant leaves, suppressing foliar diseases.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare seaweed extract for organic crops? A: Collect fresh seaweed (Ascophyllum, Sargassum, or Kappaphycus). Rinse with fresh water. Blend with water in 1:5 ratio. Strain and dilute further 1:10 for foliar spray. Apply once a week. Commercial liquid seaweed extracts are also available; dilute as per label (typically 2–4 mL/L). Seaweed provides cytokinins, auxins, betaines, and micronutrients that improve germination, tillering, and stress tolerance.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare humic acid solution from leonardite or coal? A: Dissolve 50 g leonardite/vermicompost (humic-rich) in 1 L water with a few drops of potassium hydroxide (pH adjuster) to extract humates. Filter after 1 hour. Apply as soil drench (5 L/ha) at sowing. Commercial humic acid granules are easier: dissolve 1 g/L for drip application. Humic acid chelates micronutrients, improves CEC, and stimulates root elongation.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare mustard cake fertiliser for organic use? A: Soak 2 kg mustard (sarson) cake in 20 L water for 7 days, stirring daily. Filter the dark brown liquid and dilute 1:5 with water. Apply as soil drench near the root zone @ 1 L per plant for vegetables, or 100 L/acre via irrigation. Dry mustard cake can also be applied directly @ 200–250 kg/ha as basal dose, providing 5–6% N, 2% P, and 1.5% K.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare neem cake fertiliser for soil application? A: Neem cake is the residue after cold-pressing neem seeds for oil. It contains 5.2% N, 1% P, 1.4% K, and nimbidin (pest repellent). Mix neem cake into soil @ 100–200 kg/ha two weeks before planting. It suppresses root-knot nematodes, termites, and white grubs while slowly releasing nitrogen. Can also be mixed with FYM in compost pile.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare a pyrethrum-based organic spray? A: Dry pyrethrum flower heads (Chrysanthemum cinerariifolium) for 3–4 days. Grind to powder. Soak 100 g powder in 1 L of vegetable oil overnight. Filter and add 5 mL soap to 1 L water, then mix in the oil extract slowly. Dilute the whole mixture to 10 L. Spray at dusk; pyrethrins degrade rapidly in sunlight (half-life 12 hours). Effective broad-spectrum insecticide allowed in organic farming.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Azolla biofertiliser for my paddy field? A: Collect 10–20 kg fresh Azolla from a clean water source. Spread 500 g/m² on nursery trays in 5 cm standing water enriched with 200 g superphosphate (or bone meal) per 100 m² tray. Harvest doubles every 3–5 days. Incorporate 10 t Azolla/ha into the rice field 10 days before transplanting, providing 20–30 kg N/ha. Alternatively maintain as a dual crop in standing paddy water.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare banana stem juice as a potassium fertiliser? A: Chop 5 kg fresh banana stems into small pieces. Press or crush to extract juice (approximately 3–4 L). Dilute 1:5 with water. Apply as soil drench near plant base @ 1–2 L per plant for potassium-hungry crops like potato, tomato, and banana itself. Banana stem also contains Ca, Mg, and B. Can be added to Jeevamrut preparation as a potassium booster.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare rock phosphate slurry for organic crops? A: Dissolve 50 kg rock phosphate powder in 200 L water in a drum. Add 10 L cow urine and stir. Allow to ferment for 7 days. The acid from fermentation slowly solubilises phosphorus. Apply directly to soil 2 weeks before planting @ 200–250 L/acre. Alternatively, mix rock phosphate with 500 g PSB culture per 100 kg and apply as basal for enhanced P release.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Sour Fermented Liquid (SFL) from kitchen waste? A: Fill a sealed container with vegetable peels, fruit waste, and a handful of soil as starter. Add 1 L water and 1 tbsp jaggery to feed microbes. Seal and ferment for 10–15 days (the liquid turns sour, pH 3–4). Dilute 1:100 for soil drench. The acidic, microbe-rich liquid improves nutrient solubilisation in alkaline soils and feeds beneficial soil bacteria.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare diatomaceous earth (DE) for organic pest control? A: Food-grade diatomaceous earth is ready to use. Dust lightly (100–200 g/ha) on plant surfaces where insects crawl. Alternatively mix 1 kg DE in 20 L water with a few drops of soap; spray and allow to dry on leaves. DE works by physically abrading the exoskeleton of insects, causing dehydration. Reapply after rain. Avoid inhaling during application; wear a mask.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare onion-garlic-chilli extract spray? A: Blend 200 g onion + 100 g garlic + 100 g green chilli in 1 L water. Strain through fine cloth. Add 5 mL liquid soap and dilute to 10 L. Spray on plants weekly to repel sucking insects, aphids, and mites. The combined sulphur compounds from onion and garlic act as natural fumigants at the leaf surface.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare biodynamic preparation BD 500 (horn manure)? A: Fill a cow horn completely with fresh dung from a lactating cow. Bury it 30–40 cm deep in healthy soil during autumn (around October). Dig up in spring (March–April) after winter soil rhythms have worked on it. The transformed material inside smells like rich humus. Stir 1 teaspoon in 13 L of warm water for exactly 60 minutes, alternating directions. Spray across 1 acre at sunset.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare and use Trichogramma cards for biological pest control? A: Purchase Trichogramma chilonis or T. japonicum cards from a biocontrol lab. Each card has parasitised eggs that will hatch as adult wasps. Tear cards into 10 pieces and staple to plant stems 1 m above ground, shaded from direct sun. Place @ 1 card (50,000 parasitised eggs)/ha. Repeat 3 times at weekly intervals starting when moth pests begin laying eggs.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare and use pheromone traps in the field? A: Assemble a funnel trap or delta trap. Insert the species-specific lure (e.g., Helicoverpa, FAW, or fruit fly lure) in the clip/holder at the centre of the trap. Fill the bottom container with soapy water (to drown trapped moths). Install @ 5 traps/ha at canopy height. Monitor weekly; record moth count for pest pressure assessment. Replace lure every 3–4 weeks.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare yellow sticky traps for whitefly and aphid control? A: Coat 30 cm × 20 cm yellow cardboard sheets with sticky material (petroleum jelly, castor oil, or commercial adhesive). Attach to bamboo sticks at canopy height. Install @ 8–10 traps/ha. Inspect and replace when surface is covered with insects or dust (every 7–14 days). Yellow attracts whitefly, aphids, leaf miners, and thrips; use blue traps for thrips specifically.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare and apply Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) spray? A: Purchase commercial Bt WP (wettable powder). Mix 2 g Bt/L of water with 1 mL soap as a spreader. Spray in the late afternoon or early evening (UV light degrades Bt protein rapidly). Target young larvae (1st–2nd instar) for maximum kill efficiency. Repeat every 5–7 days if pest pressure persists. Bt is harmless to humans, birds, bees, and beneficial insects.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare a simple organic fungicide using baking soda? A: Dissolve 5 g sodium bicarbonate (baking soda) in 1 L water. Add 5 mL vegetable oil and 2 mL liquid soap. Emulsify by shaking well. Spray every 7 days as a preventive for powdery mildew on cucurbits, roses, and grapes. Baking soda raises leaf surface pH to ~8.3, inhibiting fungal spore germination. Use potassium bicarbonate for a more effective and NPOP-compliant version.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Cassia tora leaf extract for organic pest control? A: Boil 2 kg Cassia tora (chakramard/foetid cassia) leaves in 5 L water for 20 minutes. Cool and filter. Add 20 mL soap and dilute to 10 L. Spray on crops affected by spider mites and powdery mildew. Cassia leaves contain anthraquinones and chrysophanic acid that are toxic to mites and fungal pathogens.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare fermented cowpea or legume extract for nitrogen nutrition? A: Soak 1 kg dry cowpea (or soybean/green gram) in 5 L water for 24 hours. Blend or grind the soaked seeds with soaking water. Ferment for 48 hours in a covered container. Dilute 1:10 and apply as soil drench near root zone. The amino acids and readily available N from the fermenting legumes provide a quick nitrogen boost to soil microbes and plants.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare copper sulphate solution for organic disease control? A: Weigh out 1 kg copper sulphate (blue vitriol). Dissolve in 50 L water in a plastic or wooden vessel (never iron). In a separate container dissolve 1 kg slaked lime in 50 L water. Test copper sulphate solution with litmus; slowly add lime water to it while stirring until the solution turns alkaline (pH >7). This is 1% Bordeaux mixture. Use within 30 minutes of preparation.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare banana pseudostem ash fertiliser? A: Dry banana pseudostem pieces in sun for 5–7 days until completely desiccated. Burn in an open pit and collect the white/grey ash. This ash contains 40–50% K₂O, 5–10% P₂O₅, and significant Ca and Mg. Store dry in sealed bags. Apply 200–300 kg/ha before the last ploughing or mix 1 kg ash in 20 L water and apply as liquid around plant base for fruiting crops.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare insect-killing soap spray? A: Dissolve 5 g pure soap (castile soap or pure potassium soap; not detergent) in 1 L water. Test on a few leaves for 24 hours before full application to check phytotoxicity. Spray directly on insects (contact action only). Effective against soft-bodied pests: aphids, whitefly, mealybugs, spider mites. Rinse plant with plain water 2 hours after application to prevent leaf burn.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare a vermi-wash liquid fertiliser? A: Vermi-wash is the liquid that drips through an active worm bin. Install a tap at the bottom of the worm bin. Collect the dark brownish liquid after watering the top of the bin. Dilute 1:10 with water before foliar application or 1:5 for soil drench. It is rich in plant growth hormones, enzymes, humic acids, and beneficial microbes. Apply once a week for best results.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare Sunhemp green manure for nitrogen enrichment? A: Sow Sunhemp (Crotalaria juncea) seed @ 25–30 kg/ha in broadcast or line sowing before the main crop. Apply minimal starter irrigation. Incorporate green biomass by ploughing at 45 days when plants are at 50% flowering stage. Sunhemp adds 80–100 kg N/ha and 15–20 tonnes of green biomass. The deep taproot also breaks hardpan and improves drainage.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare and use marigold as a trap crop? A: Sow African marigold (Tagetes erecta) @ 1 row per 16 rows of main crop (tomato, brinjal, or potato). Transplant 15–20 days before the main crop so it is flowering when the main crop is young. Marigold root exudates suppress root-knot nematodes; flowers attract and trap Helicoverpa moths. Destroy marigold plants along with egg masses every 15 days.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare castor oil spray as a mole/rodent repellent? A: Mix 60 mL castor oil with 2 tbsp dish soap and blend until foamy. Add 2 L water and shake well. Dilute 45 mL of this concentrate in 4 L water. Spray generously on the soil surface and around burrow openings after rain or watering when soil is moist. Castor oil irritates the digestive systems of moles, gophers, and rats, encouraging them to relocate without harming them.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do I prepare a fermented weed fertiliser (weed tea)? A: Fill a drum 1/3 with weed biomass (avoid seeding weeds). Top with water. Weigh down weeds to keep submerged. Cover and ferment for 3–4 weeks. Stir twice a week. The foul-smelling dark liquid contains concentrated plant nutrients leached from the weeds. Dilute 1:10 before applying as soil drench. Common weeds used: nettle, comfrey, borage — all are mineral-rich nutrient accumulators.", "source": "Organic Input Preparation DB", "category": "organic"},

    # ── Organic Farming – 100 NEW extended Q&A chunks (batch 2) ──────────────
    {"text": "Q: What is the difference between organic and natural farming? A: Organic farming follows defined standards (NPOP, USDA NOP) and requires third-party or PGS certification, with specific input lists. Natural farming (e.g., ZBNF, Kyusei) is a philosophy-based approach using only on-farm inputs, often without formal certification. Both avoid synthetic chemicals, but organic farming has legally enforceable rules and market traceability.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the C:N ratio and why does it matter for composting? A: The carbon-to-nitrogen ratio determines decomposition speed. Ideal composting C:N is 25–30:1. High-C materials (straw, wood chips ~80:1) are 'browns'; high-N materials (green leaves, dung ~15:1) are 'greens'. Mixing browns and greens in the right ratio ensures fast decomposition without nitrogen loss or sour smell. Finished compost has C:N below 20:1.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you manage iron deficiency (chlorosis) organically in fruit crops? A: Apply chelated iron derived from EDTA-free sources (allowed under some standards) or ferrous sulphate foliar spray at 0.5%. Acidify soil near roots with elemental sulphur (500 g/plant). Apply FYM or coir pith compost to lower pH in alkaline soils. Mycorrhizal inoculation also improves iron uptake via extended hyphal network.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is zinc deficiency in crops and how is it corrected organically? A: Zinc deficiency symptoms: interveinal chlorosis on young leaves, stunted internodes, 'little leaf' in fruit trees, white bud in maize. Correct by foliar spray of zinc sulphate 0.5% twice at 10-day intervals. Apply ZnSO₄ @ 25 kg/ha to soil once in 3 years. In alkaline soils, maintain high organic matter to chelate zinc and improve availability.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of sulphur in organic crop nutrition and how is it supplied? A: Sulphur is essential for protein synthesis, amino acid formation (cysteine, methionine), and enhances flavour/pungency in alliums and crucifers. Organic sources: gypsum (calcium sulphate, 18% S), elemental sulphur (80–90% S), FYM, and mustard cake. Elemental sulphur also controls powdery mildew and mites when applied as dust or wettable sulphur.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of boron deficiency in crops? A: Boron deficiency causes hollow stem in cauliflower, top sickness in tobacco, and poor fruit set. Apply borax foliar spray at 0.2% (2 g/L) twice during vegetative and flowering stages. Soil application of borax @ 10 kg/ha once every 3 years. Do not exceed recommendations; boron toxicity threshold is only 2–3× deficiency level.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How are micro-watersheds managed on organic farms to conserve rainwater? A: Construct contour bunds at 0.5% slope to slow runoff. Build farm ponds (10% of farm area) for harvesting rainwater. Use dead furrows and tied ridges in rainfed fields. Plant vetiver grass (Khus) on bund slopes to prevent erosion. These measures recharge groundwater, extend crop water availability, and reduce flooding damage.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing salinity stress in crops? A: Grow salt-tolerant crops (barley, Karnal grass, Suaeda). Apply gypsum 4 t/ha to displace sodium. Leach salts with good irrigation during off-season. Mulch to reduce evaporation-driven salt accumulation on soil surface. Apply FYM 20+ t/ha to improve soil structure and reduce osmotic stress. Foliar spray of potassium silicate (1 g/L) improves plant salt tolerance.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of silicon in organic crop production? A: Silicon (Si) strengthens cell walls, improves lodging resistance, reduces fungal penetration, and improves drought and heat tolerance. Not considered an essential nutrient but highly beneficial. Organic sources: rice husk ash (20% SiO₂), wollastonite, and diatomaceous earth. Apply as soil amendment @ 200–500 kg/ha or foliar spray of potassium silicate solution.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of thrips in onion? A: Apply NSKE 5% spray at 10-day intervals. Use blue sticky traps @ 8–10/ha. Spray spinosad 45SC (allowed in some organic standards) @ 0.3 mL/L as a last resort. Avoid dense planting. Irrigate frequently in dry conditions (thrips prefer hot, dry weather). Mulching with reflective silver mulch reduces thrips landing on leaves.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic cultivation of medicinal plants like ashwagandha managed? A: Sow ashwagandha (Withania somnifera) in well-drained sandy loam soil. Apply FYM 5 t/ha as basal. Avoid waterlogging; roots rot quickly. For root rot, drench with Trichoderma viride. No major pest problems; aphids managed with NSKE 5%. Harvest roots 5–6 months after sowing. Organic ashwagandha commands 40–60% premium in herbal export markets.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of citrus greening (HLB) disease? A: Huanglongbing (HLB) is caused by Candidatus Liberibacter, spread by citrus psyllid. No cure exists. Prevention: remove and destroy infected trees, control psyllid with neem oil 2% + kaolin clay foliar spray, use reflective mulch, and plant psyllid-resistant rootstocks. Maintain nutritional balance (zinc, iron, magnesium) to delay symptom expression.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the importance of calcium in organic vegetable production? A: Calcium (Ca) is essential for cell wall integrity, reducing blossom-end rot (tomato, pepper), tip burn (lettuce, cabbage), and internal browning (apple). Apply gypsum @ 500 kg/ha or lime as soil amendment. Foliar spray of calcium chloride (0.5%) at fruit development stage corrects deficiency rapidly. Maintain adequate soil moisture for consistent Ca uptake.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What traditional Indian varieties are recommended for organic cultivation? A: Heritage/landrace varieties adapted to local conditions perform better under organic management. Examples: Sona Masoori and Rajamudi rice, Sharbati and Khapli wheat, Desi cotton (Gossypium arboreum), Kashi Vishwanath brinjal, Pusa Sadabahar chilli. These varieties are pest-tolerant and suited to lower-input systems.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing waterlogging and flooding on farms? A: Install sub-surface drainage tiles or open drainage channels. Raise bed height (broad-bed furrow system, BBF). Grow flood-tolerant varieties (Swarna Sub1 rice). Apply lime after flooding to restore pH. After floodwater recedes, apply FYM to replace lost topsoil nutrients. Cover crop with dhaincha to quickly restore soil organic matter.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the key differences between vermicompost and FYM in terms of crop response? A: Vermicompost has 3–5× higher nutrient concentration, better microbial load, and contains plant hormones (IAA, cytokinin) and enzymes absent in FYM. FYM is cheaper and available in larger quantities. Vermicompost at 2.5 t/ha gives similar response to FYM at 10 t/ha. Combining both is ideal: FYM as bulk organic matter + vermicompost for microbial and hormonal benefits.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming integrated with agroecology principles? A: Agroecology applies ecological science to farming system design. It goes beyond input substitution (replacing chemical with organic) to redesign farm ecosystems: diverse crop rotations, polycultures, in-situ nutrient cycling, habitat for natural enemies, water cycle management, and farmer knowledge. Organic certification is one tool within a broader agroecological framework.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of downy mildew in grapes? A: Apply Bordeaux mixture 0.5–1% preventively before rains and after infection risk. Spray copper hydroxide 0.3% every 7–10 days during monsoon. Ensure good canopy ventilation through proper pruning and tying. Remove infected bunches. Avoid overhead irrigation. Sulphur dust application (30 kg/ha) combined with copper reduces dual infection of downy + powdery mildew.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the significance of soil biological activity index in organic farming? A: Soil biological activity can be assessed by CO₂ respiration rate, enzyme activity (dehydrogenase, phosphatase), or earthworm count (>10/m² indicates healthy soil). Organic farms consistently show 30–80% higher microbial biomass carbon than conventional farms. This biological activity drives nutrient cycling, disease suppression, and aggregate stability.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic pomegranate cultivation managed? A: Apply FYM 20 kg + vermicompost 5 kg + neem cake 2 kg per plant per year. For bacterial blight, apply copper oxychloride 0.3% spray preventively. For fruit borer, use pheromone traps. Drench Trichoderma at planting and after pruning. Maintain 5 m × 5 m spacing for good aeration. Mulch basin with dry straw to conserve moisture.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of early and late blight in potato? A: Use certified disease-free seed tubers. Treat with Trichoderma + Pseudomonas slurry before planting. Apply Bordeaux mixture 1% at first symptom appearance. Follow up with copper oxychloride 0.3% every 7–10 days. Earthing-up prevents tuber greening and reduces late blight entry. Ensure 3-year rotation with non-solanaceous crops.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is soil compaction diagnosed and corrected organically? A: Compact soils show slow water infiltration, shallow root systems, and poor crop stand. Test by inserting a metal rod — hard stopping at <20 cm indicates compaction. Remediation: subsoil ploughing (chisel plough at 40–50 cm depth), followed by deep-rooted cover crops (radish, sunflower, Sunhemp taproot breaks hardpan). Regular FYM application prevents future compaction.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of mealybugs in grapes and pomegranate? A: Apply neem oil 3% + soap spray on stem and bunches. Drench around plant base with neem oil emulsion to kill soil-stage eggs. Introduce Cryptolaemus montrouzieri (mealybug destroyer beetle) @ 10 adults/plant. Remove and destroy ant colonies that protect mealybugs. Stem banding with adhesive tape prevents ant-assisted spread.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of potassium in organic crop quality? A: Potassium (K) improves fruit quality (sweetness, colour, shelf life), activates 60+ enzymes, improves drought tolerance (stomatal regulation), disease resistance, and starch synthesis. Organic K sources: wood ash, granite dust, greensand, potassium-rich FYM, banana peel ash. Potassium-rich soils reduce pest damage by strengthening cell walls against fungal and insect entry.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of powdery mildew in wheat? A: Use resistant varieties (WR544, HI8498). Adjust sowing time to avoid peak infection period. Apply wettable sulphur 0.2% spray at tillering and jointing. Maintain adequate plant nutrition — excess N worsens disease. Remove volunteer wheat plants from field margins. Soil application of potassium silicate improves resistance to fungal entry.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing root rot in chickpea? A: Seed treat with Trichoderma viride 4 g/kg + Rhizobium 200 g/10 kg seed. Apply FYM enriched with Trichoderma as basal dose. Avoid waterlogging by using raised beds. Practise 3-year rotation (avoid chickpea on the same field consecutively). Remove and destroy infected plants. Soil solarisation before sowing reduces Fusarium inoculum in the field.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the main categories of biostimulants allowed in organic farming? A: Biostimulants include: seaweed extracts (cytokinins, betaines), humic/fulvic acids (CEC improvement, chelation), amino acid hydrolysates (direct N supply, stress relief), microbial inoculants (rhizobacteria, mycorrhizae), and fermented plant preparations (FPJ, Panchagavya). These improve nutrient use efficiency and stress tolerance without providing bulk nutrition.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming adapted to dryland and semi-arid conditions? A: Key adaptations: drought-tolerant varieties (millets, sorghum, pulses), wide spacing to reduce competition, deep-rooted cover crops to mine subsoil moisture, mulching to reduce evaporation (40% saving), contour bunds, water harvesting ponds, and minimal tillage to conserve soil moisture. Organic matter building is most critical — each 1% SOM holds 170,000 L water/ha.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of stem and root rot in sunflower? A: Seed treat with Trichoderma harzianum 4 g/kg. Apply FYM-Trichoderma mixture (5 kg Trichoderma/tonne FYM) as basal dose. Avoid waterlogging. Practice rotation with cereals. For Sclerotinia wilt, remove and burn infected plants. Maintain wide row spacing (90 cm) for good air circulation that limits spore dispersal.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the organic practices for millet (bajra, jowar, ragi) cultivation? A: Apply FYM 5–7 t/ha + vermicompost 1 t/ha. Seed treat with Azospirillum 600 g/ha + PSB 600 g/ha. For shoot fly in sorghum, use resistant varieties (CSH 16R) and adjust sowing time to avoid peak fly emergence. Millets are naturally drought-tolerant and need fewer organic inputs compared to cereals, making them ideal for low-input organic systems.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is integrated nutrient management (INM) in an organic context? A: INM under organic standards combines all permitted nutrient sources: FYM, vermicompost, green manure, biofertilisers, crop residues, and mineral amendments (rock phosphate, gypsum). The goal is to match crop nutrient demand with supply from multiple sources while building soil organic matter. INM avoids over-reliance on any single input.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of leaf miner in tomato and vegetables? A: Apply neem oil 2% spray to coat leaf surface; larvae feeding on treated leaves are affected. Release Diglyphus isaea parasitoid wasps @ 1 per 5 plants. Use yellow sticky traps to reduce adult fly numbers. Remove and destroy heavily infested leaves. Spinosad 0.3 mL/L as a last resort spray (check certification standards). Avoid dense planting.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of organic farming in preserving heirloom seed biodiversity? A: Organic farms avoid GM seeds and rely on open-pollinated varieties, creating selection pressure that maintains genetic diversity. Farmer seed banks and seed-sharing networks (e.g., Navdanya in India) preserve thousands of varieties. Heirloom varieties often carry disease resistance, nutritional traits, and climate adaptability lost from modern hybrids.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing Alternaria blight in potato and tomato? A: Apply copper-based fungicide (copper oxychloride 0.3%) or Bordeaux mixture 1% preventively. Ensure adequate potassium nutrition (K strengthens epidermal resistance). Remove infected lower leaves early. Mulch soil to prevent Alternaria spore splash from soil. Rotate with non-solanaceous crops for 2–3 years.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to arid-zone horticulture? A: Use drought-hardy species (ber/jujube, pomegranate, fig, date palm, aonla/amla). Apply FYM in individual pits (50 kg/pit) at planting. Mulch basins with dry straw (10 cm deep). Use drip irrigation with mulch combination to save 60–70% water. For saline conditions, grow ber or karonda which tolerate soil EC up to 6 dS/m. Minimal spray inputs are needed as arid climate suppresses many foliar diseases.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of red spider mite in tea and vegetables? A: Spray neem oil 2% + soap 0.5% solution. Apply predatory mite Phytoseiulus persimilis @ 5–10/plant. Avoid broad-spectrum pesticide applications that kill natural predators. Increase humidity by overhead misting (spider mites prefer dry conditions). Wettable sulphur 0.3% spray is highly effective and approved under most organic standards.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What organic inputs can be used for manganese correction in acidic soils? A: In acidic soils (pH <5.5) manganese toxicity is more common than deficiency. Raise pH with lime to reduce Mn availability. For Mn deficiency (interveinal chlorosis on young leaves) in neutral/alkaline soils: apply manganese sulphate foliar spray at 0.5% twice. Incorporate FYM to chelate Mn and moderate its availability. Soil test before correction.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to soil restoration after flood damage? A: Remove silt deposits if excessive. Apply lime 2–3 t/ha if pH dropped due to flooding. Add FYM 10–15 t/ha to restore organic matter and microbial population. Sow fast-growing green manure (dhaincha) to stabilise soil structure. Apply biofertiliser package after 15 days to re-establish beneficial microbial community. Test soil for salinity if seawater flooding occurred.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of papaya ring spot virus? A: No curative treatment. Rogue out infected plants immediately. Manage vector (aphids) with neem oil 2% + soap. Use reflective mulch to confuse aphids. Plant barrier crops (maize, sorghum) at 4–5 rows around the papaya block to intercept virus-carrying aphids. Use cross-protection with mild strain (pre-immunisation) in areas where severe strains are prevalent.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic cultivation protocol for garlic and onion? A: Apply FYM 20–25 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha as basal. Treat sets/seeds with Trichoderma + Azotobacter. For purple blotch (Alternaria), spray copper oxychloride 0.3% every 7 days. For thrips, use neem oil + blue sticky traps. Avoid excess irrigation to prevent neck rot. Harvest when 50% tops fall naturally.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How are organic farms monitored for chemical contamination risks? A: Third-party inspectors check farm boundaries, irrigation water quality, input records, and neighbouring land use. Soil and crop tissue samples are tested for pesticide residues before certification. Farms must maintain 7.5 m buffer zones from conventional fields. Water sources shared with conventional farms require regular testing (quarterly minimum).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is permaculture and how is it related to organic farming? A: Permaculture designs self-sustaining agricultural ecosystems based on natural patterns. Principles include: observe and interact, use edges, integrate rather than segregate, and produce no waste. Permaculture often incorporates organic practices but focuses more on system design (food forests, polycultures, water harvesting) than specific input management. It complements organic certification.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of downy mildew in cucurbits? A: Apply Bordeaux mixture 0.5% as a preventive spray at 7-day intervals during humid weather. Use copper hydroxide 0.3% at first symptom. Ensure good air circulation through trellising and proper spacing. Remove infected leaves and vines promptly. Avoid overhead irrigation. Grow resistant varieties (downy mildew-resistant cucumber like Malini). Crop rotation with non-cucurbit crops for 2 years.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of organic farming in reducing antibiotic resistance? A: Organic livestock farming prohibits routine antibiotic use and growth promoters. This reduces selection pressure for antibiotic-resistant bacteria in manure, soil, and water. Organic manure has significantly lower antibiotic-resistant gene (ARG) loads than conventional manure. Plant-based organic farming also eliminates antibiotic residues from soil amendments.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How do you manage organic farms during extended drought conditions? A: Prioritise drought-tolerant varieties and drought-hardy species. Apply mulch (6–10 cm straw) immediately to conserve available soil moisture. Reduce plant density to lower competition. Apply potassium silicate foliar spray (1 g/L) to improve stomatal regulation. Use stored rainwater from farm ponds. Temporary deficit irrigation using AWD technique can maintain crop until rains resume.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing broccoli and cauliflower? A: Apply FYM 20 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha + boron (borax 10 kg/ha) as basal dose. Transplant 4-week-old seedlings treated with Trichoderma. For DBM (diamondback moth), apply Bt kurstaki 2 g/L in early evening. For aphids, spray NSKE 5%. Maintain soil moisture evenly to prevent buttoning and browning. Harvest cauliflower when curd is compact and white.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the economic value of organic matter in soil? A: Each 1% increase in SOM in 1 ha to 30 cm depth represents ~20 tonnes of organic matter holding 170,000 L water, 500 kg N, 100 kg P, and 100 kg K (long-term reserve). Replacing soil organic matter lost through conventional farming costs thousands of rupees in synthetic fertiliser. Building SOM through organic inputs is thus a long-term economic investment.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic cultivation protocol for sweet potato? A: Prepare ridges and furrows. Apply FYM 10 t/ha as basal. Plant vine cuttings (25–30 cm) at 30 cm spacing. For weevil (Cylas formicarius), drench pheromone traps in soil + apply entomopathogenic nematodes (Steinernema). Avoid waterlogging. Harvest when vines turn yellow, about 3.5–4 months after planting. Store in cool, dry conditions layered with dry sand.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the significance of crop residue management in organic systems? A: Returning crop residues to soil adds organic matter, reduces erosion, and feeds soil organisms. Chopped residues decompose faster. Do not burn residues — burning destroys organic matter and releases CO₂. Where residue is high (rice straw), use Trichoderma or Pusa Decomposer spray to accelerate decomposition in 25 days vs. 60+ days naturally.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to grow-and-sell directly to consumers? A: Farmer markets, community-supported agriculture (CSA) boxes, and online farm-to-fork platforms allow organic farmers to capture full retail premium. CSA subscribers pay advance for weekly vegetable boxes, providing cash flow before harvest. Direct-to-consumer sales eliminate middlemen, improving margin by 40–80% compared to mandi price.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming practised under poly-houses and net houses? A: Use coir pith compost, vermicompost, and FYM as growing media amendments. Control humidity and temperature to reduce disease pressure. Drip irrigation with fertigation using permitted liquid organics (seaweed, humic acid, fish amino acid) is highly effective. For whitefly and thrips in enclosed structures, use sticky traps + biocontrol agents (Encarsia formosa for whitefly).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of Sclerotinia rot in vegetables and oilseeds? A: Apply Trichoderma viride 5 kg/ha + FYM as soil drench. Solarise soil during summer. Practice crop rotation avoiding host crops (sunflower, mustard, soybean, French bean) in sequence. Spray Coniothyrium minitans biocontrol agent targeting Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in soil. Remove and burn infected plant debris; sclerotia can survive in soil for 5–8 years.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the main organic cropping systems practised in India? A: Major systems include: rice-wheat (Indo-Gangetic plains, organic using FYM + biofertilisers), cotton-based intercropping (Central India), spice-based systems (Kerala, Sikkim), fruit-based orchards (Himachal, Maharashtra), and vegetable clusters (peri-urban organic hubs). Each system requires tailored input and rotation strategies under NPOP guidelines.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing strawberry? A: Prepare raised beds (15 cm high) with FYM + vermicompost + cocopeat (3:1:1 mix). Mulch with black polyethylene film. Use drip irrigation. For grey mould (Botrytis), improve air circulation and apply Trichoderma spray. For two-spotted spider mite, use predatory mite Phytoseiulus persimilis. Harvest when 75% of surface turns red. Maintain cold chain (2–4°C) post-harvest.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming related to Integrated Farming Systems (IFS)? A: IFS combines crops, livestock, fish, poultry, and agro-forestry on the same farm to maximise resource recycling and income. Under organic IFS, livestock manure feeds crops, crop residues feed animals, fishpond sludge fertilises vegetables, and trees provide biomass. This closed-loop design minimises external inputs and maximises income per unit area.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of gummosis in citrus? A: Gummosis (Phytophthora) is managed by scraping infected bark, applying Bordeaux paste (thick Bordeaux mixture) on wounds, and improving drainage. Avoid injuring trunk during tillage. Apply Trichoderma + FYM around root zone. Use tolerant rootstocks (Rangpur lime, Troyer citrange). Avoid overhead irrigation. Repeat Bordeaux paste application every 6 months.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to soil health monitoring? A: Key soil health indicators for organic farms: SOM >2%, soil pH 6.0–7.0, earthworm count >10/m², microbial biomass carbon >200 mg/kg, available NPK adequate for target yield, and soil water infiltration >20 mm/hr. Conduct soil test every 2–3 years. Soil Health Card (SHC) issued by Govt of India provides baseline data and recommendations.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of root and stem borer in sugarcane? A: Release Trichogramma chilonis @ 50,000 eggs/ha at 30, 45, and 60 days after planting. Apply Metarhizium anisopliae granules at root zone for soil-stage larvae. For internode borer, spray NSKE 5% at 90-day crop age. Avoid ratooning in heavily infested fields. Use trash mulching to maintain soil moisture and reduce pest establishment.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the benefits and challenges of organic aquaponics? A: Organic aquaponics integrates fish production with plant cultivation in a recirculating water system. Benefits: year-round production, 90–95% water saving, high productivity per unit area, no soil needed. Challenges under organic certification: approved fish feed sources, managing algae, temperature control, high setup cost, and system complexity. NPOP currently has limited specific guidelines for aquaponics.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How are organic farms assessed for soil erosion risk and managed? A: Assess slope angle, soil texture, rainfall intensity, and ground cover. Practices to prevent erosion: maintain 70%+ ground cover at all times via cover crops or mulch, construct contour bunds on slopes >2%, avoid bare soil in monsoon, plant vetiver or napier grass on bunds, and use no-till or minimum till to preserve soil aggregates.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of grey mould (Botrytis cinerea) in vegetables? A: Improve air circulation through proper spacing and canopy management. Remove infected plant parts immediately. Apply Trichoderma harzianum 5 g/L as foliar spray. Avoid overhead irrigation, especially in evening. Copper oxychloride 0.3% spray as a preventive during cool, humid weather. Potassium-rich nutrition strengthens cell walls against Botrytis penetration.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of traditional farming knowledge in modern organic agriculture? A: Traditional ecological knowledge (TEK) includes local variety selection, seasonal planting calendars, pest indicators, natural pesticide recipes, and soil management practices accumulated over centuries. Modern organic farming integrates TEK with scientific validation — e.g., the documented efficacy of neem, Jeevamrut, Panchagavya, and Azolla that were traditional practices long before scientific study.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of leaf curl in chilli and capsicum? A: Leaf curl is caused by thrips-transmitted Chilli Leaf Curl Virus (ChLCV). Remove and destroy infected plants immediately. Control thrips vector with neem oil 2% spray and blue sticky traps. Use virus-free nursery seedlings. Reflective silver mulch deters thrips. Spray mineral oil 1% to reduce virus acquisition by thrips on infected plants.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing post-harvest diseases in mango? A: Use Trichoderma viride or T. harzianum dip treatment (5 g/L) at 52°C for 5 minutes after harvest to suppress anthracnose and stem end rot. Store at 12–13°C (below 10°C causes chilling injury). Pack in ventilated boxes. Avoid bruising during harvesting. In transit, maintain cold chain. Wax coating with food-grade carnauba wax extends shelf life.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing medicinal mushrooms (Reishi, Shiitake, Oyster)? A: Use organic substrates: rice straw, wheat straw, paddy husk, sugarcane bagasse, or saw dust from untreated wood. Pasteurise substrate with hot water at 80°C for 2 hours (instead of chemical sterilisation). Inoculate with spawn in sterilised bags. Maintain 70–80% humidity and 20–30°C temperature. Organic certification requires fully organic substrate and no synthetic additives.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of yellow mosaic virus in soybean? A: Yellow mosaic is spread by whitefly. Control vector with neem oil 2% + yellow sticky traps. Rogue out infected plants immediately. Use resistant varieties (JS 335, JS 93-05). Reflective mulch deters whitefly. Border crops of maize or sorghum reduce virus spread into the main field. No curative treatment — early rogueing and vector control are the only strategies.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach for growing spices like cardamom and pepper? A: Apply FYM 5 kg + vermicompost 2 kg + neem cake 500 g per plant annually in pits. Shade management is critical; cardamom requires 50% shade. For thrips in cardamom, spray neem oil 2%. For Phytophthora root rot in pepper, drench Trichoderma + Pseudomonas. Maintain mulch of dried leaves around plants to conserve moisture in hill slopes.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing sesame (til)? A: Sesame performs well in low-fertility conditions and is an ideal entry crop for conversion to organic. Apply FYM 5 t/ha as basal. Seed treat with Rhizobium (sesame has limited nodulation, Azospirillum is more effective). For Alternaria blight, spray copper oxychloride 0.3%. Sesame has a short duration (75–90 days) and can fit into many organic rotations.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the impact of organic farming on soil carbon sequestration? A: Organic farms sequester an additional 50–200 kg C/ha/year compared to conventional, mainly due to higher organic matter inputs and reduced tillage. Over 20 years, organically managed soils can accumulate 0.5–1% more SOM. Converting 50% of India's farmland to organic practices could potentially sequester 50–100 Mt CO₂e/year, contributing to climate change mitigation.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of Helicoverpa armigera (pod borer) in chickpea? A: Install pheromone traps (Helicoverpa lure) @ 5/ha for monitoring. Spray Bt (Bacillus thuringiensis var. kurstaki) @ 2 g/L at egg-hatching stage. Apply NSKE 5% twice at 7-day intervals. Introduce Chrysoperla carnea (green lacewing) eggs @ 50,000/ha. Use resistant varieties (ICCC-37, Phule G-08). Practice intercropping with coriander to attract predatory wasps.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic poultry management integrated with crop production? A: Free-range poultry forages in crop fields after harvest, consuming insects and weed seeds while depositing manure (high N). Chicken manure (1.1% N, 0.8% P, 0.5% K) can be composted and applied to crops. Avoid applying fresh poultry manure within 90 days of harvest (food safety). Organic poultry standards prohibit routine antibiotics and require access to pasture and organic feed.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of blast disease in finger millet (ragi)? A: Use resistant varieties (GPU-28, HR-911). Treat seeds with hot water at 52°C for 10 minutes or Trichoderma 4 g/kg. Spray fermented garlic extract (50 g garlic/L) at 21 and 35 days after sowing. Avoid dense planting; maintain 22.5 × 10 cm spacing. Avoid excess nitrogen application which promotes blast susceptibility.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic market premium and how do farmers access it? A: Organic certified produce commands 20–50% premium over conventional in domestic markets and up to 100% in export markets. Access premium markets through: organic cooperatives (e.g., Spices Board certified), APEDA-registered exporters, direct-to-consumer channels (farmers markets, CSA), certified organic stores, and e-commerce platforms (Organic India, 24 Mantra). PGS-India certification is often sufficient for domestic premium.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to mango flower and fruit drop management? A: Apply potassium nitrate (KNO₃ – verify under standard) or wood ash solution (100 g/L) at bud burst to promote uniform flowering. For fruit drop, spray seaweed extract (3 mL/L) + calcium foliar (0.5%) at pea size and marble size fruit stages. Ensure adequate boron (0.2% borax) at full bloom for better fruit set and retention.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing rice in upland (rainfed) conditions? A: Select drought-tolerant upland varieties (Sahabhagi Dhan, DRR Dhan 44). Apply FYM 5 t/ha + Azospirillum + PSB seed treatment. Establish on contour to conserve rainwater. No standing water maintained; rely on natural rainfall. Apply Jeevamrut 200 L/acre twice a season. For blast under rainfed conditions, spray fermented garlic–ginger extract.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the relationship between organic farming and food safety? A: Organic produce has lower pesticide residue loads (multiple studies confirm 30–70% lower residues) and lower risk of antibiotic-resistant bacteria. However, organic farms using fresh manure carry a risk of pathogens (Salmonella, E. coli O157:H7). NPOP mandates a 120-day interval between raw manure application and harvest of soil-contact crops, and 90 days for above-ground crops.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How is organic farming regulated and promoted by the Indian government? A: Key government initiatives: National Programme for Organic Production (NPOP) – sets standards and accreditation; Paramparagat Krishi Vikas Yojana (PKVY) – provides Rs 50,000/ha/3 years support to farmer clusters; Mission Organic Value Chain Development (MOVCDNER) – promotes organic value chains in Northeast India; and PM-PRANAM scheme incentivises chemical fertiliser reduction.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of bacterial wilt in tomato and brinjal? A: Use resistant varieties (Arka Rakshak, Arka Abhed). Graft susceptible varieties on resistant rootstocks. Apply Pseudomonas fluorescens 2 kg/ha as soil drench at transplanting. Solarise soil for 6 weeks before planting. Avoid waterlogging. Remove and burn wilted plants immediately. Three-year rotation with non-solanaceous crops is mandatory.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the PKVY scheme and how does it help organic farmers? A: Paramparagat Krishi Vikas Yojana (PKVY) promotes cluster-based organic farming. Rs 50,000/ha support over 3 years covers inputs, certification, and market linkage. Farmers form clusters of 50 (at least 50 acres). The scheme covers: conversion costs, organic input procurement, PGS certification, capacity building, and value addition. Applied through the state agriculture department.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing guava? A: Apply FYM 30 kg + vermicompost 8 kg + neem cake 3 kg per tree per year in two split doses. For fruit fly, use methyl eugenol traps (1:6 methyl eugenol: malathion — check organic compliance) or protein hydrolysate-based traps. For wilt (Fusarium), drench Trichoderma + Pseudomonas. Bag developing fruits with paper bags for protection from flies in organic orchards.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the role of plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria (PGPR) in organic farming? A: PGPR colonise plant roots and promote growth via: nitrogen fixation (Azotobacter, Rhizobium), phosphate solubilisation (Bacillus megaterium), phytohormone production (IAA, GA, cytokinin), siderophore production (iron chelation), and pathogen suppression (antibiotic secretion). PGPR inoculants reduce need for chemical N and P by 25–50% and improve crop establishment.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing fennel (saunf) and coriander? A: Both are light-feeding crops suited to organic production. Apply FYM 5–7 t/ha + vermicompost 1 t/ha. Treat seeds with Azospirillum + PSB. For powdery mildew on coriander, spray wettable sulphur 0.2%. For aphids on fennel, apply NSKE 5% or tobacco decoction. Harvest seed crops when 70% umbels turn yellow. Essential oils in organic coriander and fennel are significantly higher than conventional.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing okra (bhindi)? A: Apply FYM 15 t/ha + vermicompost 2.5 t/ha as basal. Seed treat with Trichoderma + Azotobacter. For YVMV (Yellow Vein Mosaic Virus), control whitefly vector with neem oil 2% + yellow sticky traps. Use resistant varieties (Parbhani Kranti, Arka Anamika). For fruit borer, apply Bt kurstaki 2 g/L in evening at egg-hatching stage. Harvest every 2 days to maintain quality and yield.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to goat and sheep farming integrated with crops? A: Goats and sheep graze crop residues and weeds, reducing external feed costs. Their dung (1.4% N, 0.5% P, 1.2% K) when composted provides a balanced organic manure. Goat manure is 'hot' (high N) and should be composted before application. Grazing management is essential — avoid overgrazing which causes soil compaction and erosion, especially on slopes.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of bacterial leaf blight (BLB) in rice? A: BLB (Xanthomonas oryzae) is controlled by: seed treatment with Pseudomonas fluorescens 10 g/kg; foliar spray of copper oxychloride 0.3% at symptom appearance; and Trichoderma soil drench at transplanting. Avoid excess nitrogen and waterlogging. Plant-to-plant spacing per SRI method reduces humidity in canopy, limiting BLB spread.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What are the principles of no-till organic farming? A: No-till organic farming avoids mechanical soil disturbance to preserve soil structure, earthworm populations, fungal networks, and aggregate stability. Cover crops and mulches suppress weeds instead of tillage. Initial weed control challenges are managed through thick mulch layers (15 cm), solarisation, or flame weeding (check organic compliance). Long-term no-till improves SOM 20–40% faster than tilled organic systems.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to growing saffron in high-altitude conditions? A: Saffron (Crocus sativus) requires well-drained, calcium-rich soil. Apply FYM 10 t/ha + bone meal 200 kg/ha in planting trenches. Plant corms in July–August. For corm rot (Fusarium), drench Trichoderma before planting. Collect stigmas by hand in October–November at flower opening. Organic Kashmiri saffron (GI-tagged) commands Rs 2–3 lakh/kg in premium markets.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of stem nematode in onion and garlic? A: Drench soil with neem cake extract (250 kg/ha). Apply Purpureocillium lilacinum (formerly Paecilomyces) biocontrol @ 2.5 kg/ha mixed with FYM. Solarise soil for 6 weeks in summer. Practice 3-year rotation; avoid replanting alliums after alliums. Hot water treatment of planting material (46°C for 20 minutes) kills stem nematode in corms and bulbs.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to managing white fly in cotton? A: Spray neem oil 3% + soap 0.5% every 7 days. Use yellow sticky traps @ 8/ha. Introduce Encarsia formosa (parasitic wasp) at 5 adults/m². Avoid planting cotton near tomato or brinjal which serve as whitefly reservoirs. Use reflective silver mulch between rows. Scout weekly; spray only when whitefly count exceeds 2 adults/leaf economic threshold.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of mango malformation disease? A: Mango malformation (Fusarium mangiferae) causes vegetative and floral malformation. Prune and burn malformed parts 15 cm below visible malformation. Spray copper oxychloride 0.3% + neem oil 1% immediately after pruning. Apply Trichoderma harzianum as soil drench around the tree. Maintain tree vigour with adequate FYM and micronutrient nutrition. No fully reliable cure — prevention by sanitation is the key.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic approach to coffee and tea cultivation? A: Coffee: Apply FYM/compost 5 kg/plant + vermicompost 2 kg + neem cake 500 g annually. For white stem borer, apply Metarhizium anisopliae. For leaf rust, spray Bordeaux mixture 0.5%. Tea: Apply tea waste compost 4–5 t/ha. Manage blister blight with Bordeaux mixture. Organic coffee and tea receive 30–60% premium in export markets (Rainforest Alliance, EU Organic).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: How does the organic farming movement connect with food and farming policy in India? A: The 2019 Andhra Pradesh ZBNF Policy, Sikkim Organic Mission (2016), India's Organic Export Policy under APEDA, and the National Agroecology Policy (under development) all reflect growing policy support for organic farming. The Union Budget 2022–23 promoted natural farming along river Ganga corridor (Namami Gange organic corridor). These policies aim to reduce chemical import bill and improve farmer income.", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
    {"text": "Q: What is the organic management of thrips and TSWV (Tospo virus) in groundnut? A: Control western flower thrips (vector of TSWV) with blue/yellow sticky traps + neem oil 2% spray. Rogue out infected plants (symptoms: bronzing, ring spots). Use virus-free planting material and resistant varieties (TAG-24, ICGV-91114). Reflective silver mulch reduces thrips landing. Spray spinosad 45 SC 0.3 mL/L (verify organic status of product for your standard).", "source": "Organic Farming DB", "category": "organic"},
